thread.title: Royals rally in 7th, lead ALCS 2-0 over Blue Jays
thread.title_full: Royals rally in 7th, lead ALCS 2-0 over Blue Jays

author: courier-journal.com
title: Royals rally in 7th, lead ALCS 2-0 over Blue Jays
text:
KANSAS CITY, Mo. – Breaking down the American League Championship Series between the Kansas City Royals and Toronto Blue Jays in Game 2 from Kauffman Stadium:
Royals 6, Blue Jays 3, Royals lead series, 2-0.
***
The final: After doing absolutely nothing against Blue Jays starter David Price for the first six innings, the Royals erupted for five runs in the seventh on their way to a thrilling comeback win.
Price allowed a leadoff single in the first to Alcides Escobar then seemed to be on cruise control as he retired the next 18 batters in a row. But the pesky Royals strung together six hits to score five runs in the seventh and overcome an early 3-0 deficit.
Left-hander Danny Duffy pitched a scoreless inning to get the win, while Price took the loss to fall to 2-7 in his postseason career.
***
State of the Series: The series now shifts to Rogers Centre in Toronto, where the Blue Jays went an AL-best 53-28 during the regular season (though they did lose two of three at home in the AL Division Series).
Toronto will send right-hander Marcus Stroman to the mound against Johnny Cueto of the Royals.
Stroman tore the ACL in his knee during spring training and was expected to miss the entire season, but he worked his way back from surgery and won all four of his regular season starts in September (with a 1.67 ERA). He also started twice in the Division Series vs. Texas, including the decisive Game 5, but did not factor into either decision.
Cueto (11-13, 3.44 ERA) was acquired from Cincinnati to be the Royals ace down the stretch, but it didn’t really work out that way. In 13 starts with Kansas City, he went 4-7 with a 4.76 ERA. However, the Dominican right-hander did pitch eight masterful innings in the Royals’ Game 5 ALDS win over Houston.
Both will be working on regular rest.
***
Needing a mulligan: The Blue Jays had a miscommunication on defense in the bottom of the seventh that ended Price’s streak of 18 consecutive outs – and opened the floodgates for the Royals’ big inning.
On a fairly routine-looking popup by Ben Zobrist to shallow right field to lead off the inning, second baseman Ryan Goins and right fielder Jose Bautista converged without anyone taking charge. The ball fell between them for a single.
Two batters later, Zobrist scored the Royals’ first run. In addition the fourth and fifth runs in the inning scored with two outs.
***
Game 2 pivot point: Price had been so dominant that it didn’t seem like the misplay would hurt him.
But the Royals followed it up with consecutive singles from Lorenzo Cain (that extended his postseason hitting streak 11 games) and Eric Hosmer to score their first run.
An RBI groundout from Kendrys Morales made it a one-run game.
That brought left-handed hitting Mike Moustakas to the plate against the Jays southpaw. In his career, Moustakas is a .233/.289/.376 hitter against left-handed pitching … but this season was his best vs. lefties at .282/.338/.485.
Battling back from a 1-2 count, Moustakas lined single to right to bring home Hosmer from second and tie the game at 3.
One of the Royals’ playoff heroes last year, Moustakas was hitless in his last 13 at-bats in this year’s postseason before his game-tying single.
After Salvador Perez struck out, Alex Gordon – another left-handed hitter – doubled home Moustakas for the go-ahead run and Alex Rios capped the inning with an RBI single to score Gordon.
***
Man of the moment: In addition to his heroics in the seventh, Moustakas delivered an insurance run with an RBI single in the eighth off reliever Aaron Loup – another southpaw.
He finished 2-for-4 with a double, a single and two RBI.
***
Manager's special: Kansas City starter Yordano Ventura – as is the case with most pitchers – is much less effective going through the order a third time. How much less?
First time: .640 OPS
Second time: .661 OPS
Third time: .854 OPS
Manager Ned Yost faced a decision point in the top of the sixth with the Royals trailing 1-0 and the Blue Jays’ Nos. 2, 3 and 4 hitters due up.
As was the case with the Royals’ Game 1 starter Edinson Volquez, Ventura allowed the first two batters in the sixth to reach base.
Again, Yost stuck with his starter, but after working the count full Edwin Encarnacion – bad hand and all – grounded a single up the middle to make the score 2-0.
With his pitch count at 83 and Luke Hochevar warming in the bullpen, pitching coach Dave Eiland made a visit to the mound.
Ventura remained in the game and struck out Chris Colabello for the first out. But Troy Tulowitzki drilled an RBI double to right that fell just beyond the reach of a diving Alex Rios to give the Jays a three-run cushion.
Ventura faced one more batter, walking Russell Martin to put runners on first and second with one out, before he left the game.
Had the Royals offense not exploded for five runs in the seventh, Yost could have faced a flood of second-guessing for not going to Hochevar earlier in an effort to limit the damage.
***
What you missed on TV: Actor Eric Stonestreet of the ABC comedy series Modern Family didn’t get any TV time with the ALCS airing on a competing network, but he made his presence felt at Kauffman Stadium.
Stonestreet – a native of Kansas City, Kansas, and a big Royals fan – was featured on the stadium’s video board during the Game 2 to a rousing ovation just before the Royals mounted their seventh-inning rally. He also paid a visit to the Royals clubhouse afterward.
“Stonestreet came in just fired the boys up a little bit, gave us a little congratulations,” Royals first baseman Eric Hosmer said. “We gave him a little credit for firing us up at the beginning of that inning.”
